I definitely want to hear if
you all can think of more.

5
00:00:12.400 --> 00:00:15.431
Sometimes you're the coach,
sometimes I'm coaching people,

6
00:00:15.431 --> 00:00:16.817
calling players on the side.

7
00:00:16.817 --> 00:00:20.940
And I really like the coach metaphor,
because I'm not playing the game.

8
00:00:20.940 --> 00:00:22.056
I'm an expert at the game.

9
00:00:22.056 --> 00:00:25.371
I know the plays, I know what it looks
like, I know different scenarios, but

10
00:00:25.371 --> 00:00:27.130
I'm not actually playing the game.

11
00:00:27.130 --> 00:00:29.914
And it doesn't matter which sport
you're thinking of in your head.

12
00:00:29.914 --> 00:00:31.649
The coach is on the side.

13
00:00:31.649 --> 00:00:35.460
Sometimes, they gotta be
tough with the people.

14
00:00:35.460 --> 00:00:37.584
Sometimes they gotta be like,
you did really well there.

15
00:00:37.584 --> 00:00:40.129
And that's a lot of what what you
do as an engineering manager.

16
00:00:41.160 --> 00:00:43.128
Sometimes you're just a cheerleader.

17
00:00:43.128 --> 00:00:44.400
The team is functioning.

18
00:00:44.400 --> 00:00:44.908
They don't need you.

19
00:00:44.908 --> 00:00:45.939
They don't need to listen to you.

20
00:00:45.939 --> 00:00:47.679
In fact, if I was saying anything,

21
00:00:47.679 --> 00:00:51.280
it would actually pull them away
from what they are doing well.

22
00:00:51.280 --> 00:00:52.420
If, again, pick any sport,

23
00:00:52.420 --> 00:00:55.386
if the team's doing well, I don't need
to be on the like, do this, do that,

24
00:00:55.386 --> 00:00:58.743
because they're already functioning well,
and sometimes I'm just a cheerleader.

25
00:00:58.743 --> 00:01:00.032
Good job.

26
00:01:00.032 --> 00:01:01.142
Way to go, team.

27
00:01:01.142 --> 00:01:03.841
Keep going,
I just wanna keep them going, but

28
00:01:03.841 --> 00:01:06.208
t I don't actually need to do anything.

29
00:01:06.208 --> 00:01:07.727
Sometimes, I'm a therapist.

30
00:01:07.727 --> 00:01:09.999
You get to know your team,
you talk about personal problems,

31
00:01:09.999 --> 00:01:12.790
you talk about things they
don't share with other people.

32
00:01:12.790 --> 00:01:16.283
Sometimes your job is to listen and
provide sometimes life advice.

33
00:01:16.283 --> 00:01:18.750
Sometimes I mentor.

34
00:01:19.950 --> 00:01:21.863
Now, what should I do in the situation?

35
00:01:21.863 --> 00:01:25.210
Okay, here's what I would do or here's,
here's some approaches I would take.

36
00:01:25.210 --> 00:01:27.725
I won't go through all these, but

37
00:01:27.725 --> 00:01:32.768
there's a lot of roles that you will
play as an engineering manager.

38
00:01:32.768 --> 00:01:36.630
And what role that is,
I'll tell you a secret.

39
00:01:36.630 --> 00:01:38.353
No one tells you what you need to do.

40
00:01:38.353 --> 00:01:39.510
You have to figure that out.

41
00:01:39.510 --> 00:01:42.320
You have to figure out what you
need to be in that situation.

42
00:01:42.320 --> 00:01:45.572
Is this the time to be a peacemaker if
people are arguing about something?

43
00:01:45.572 --> 00:01:49.804
You need to step in with a firm hand and
say, hey, I bet you,

44
00:01:49.804 --> 00:01:53.130
you let's come together and
figure this out.

45
00:01:53.130 --> 00:01:54.883
Or sometimes you need to say,
you know what,

46
00:01:54.883 --> 00:01:56.418
we spent three months arguing on this.

47
00:01:56.418 --> 00:01:58.812
Here's what we're going to do,
and that's that.

48
00:01:58.812 --> 00:02:02.175
And let's move forward.

49
00:02:02.175 --> 00:02:04.060
Speaker of the House, I like this one.

50
00:02:04.060 --> 00:02:09.050
The Speaker of the House is the, for
those of you familiar with politics,

51
00:02:09.050 --> 00:02:11.558
you're the tiebreaker sometimes.

52
00:02:11.558 --> 00:02:13.518
